          "title": "Connecting Thin Clients with A2A APIs for QriptoCENT Services",
          "type": "tutorial",
          "format": "article",
          "content": {},
          "excerpt": "Use the AigentiQ SDK and A2A APIs to expose QriptoCENT-priced capabilities from thin client apps.",
          "placement": {
            "tab": "dev",
            "imageX": 50,
            "imageY": 50,
            "section": "21knowdz",
            "position": 3,
            "imageScale": 100,
            "imagePosition": "center"
          },
          "modalities": {
            "link": {
              "url": "https://qripto.net/docs/aigentiq/a2a-thin-clients",
              "allow_embed": false
            },
            "read": {
              "text": "# Connecting thin clients with A2A APIs for QriptoCENT services\n\nThin clients in the Qripto ecosystem are intentionally lightweight: they present UI and local context while delegating heavy lifting to Aigents. This tutorial shows how to expose QriptoCENT-priced services from a thin client through an A2A style API.\n\n## Why A2A matters for QriptoCENT\n\nAgent to Agent flows are central to QriptoCENT:\n\n- A user facing Aigent mediates UI, intent and permissions\n- Specialist Aigents perform pricing, trading or risk checks\n- QriptoCENT moves between parties as a result of their negotiations\n\nThe AigentiQ SDK lets you formalise these flows as API endpoints that thin clients can call.\n\n## 1. Define the external capability\n\nStart by defining a single, clear capability, for example:\n\n- `POST /api/qriptopian/preview-chapter`\n\nThe contract might be: the caller submits a persona token and a `chapter_id`, your backend:\n\n- Checks entitlements\n- If needed, prices a preview in Q¢\n- Executes a QriptoCENT micro-payment\n- Returns a signed URL to the preview content\n\n## 2. Implement the backend endpoint\n\nUse a lightweight HTTP framework and inside the handler:\n\n- Authenticate the thin client or tenant application\n- Resolve the end user persona from the token it passes\n- Use AigentiQ SDK helpers to call a pricing Aigent and construct a payment request\n- Trigger QriptoCENT movement and wait for confirmation\n\nKeep the handler itself small: the real work lives in Aigents and iQube operations.\n\n## 3. Keep iQube boundaries clear\n\nFor each step, identify the iQubes in play:\n\n- A content iQube for the chapter or preview asset\n- A relationship or entitlement iQube for the caller and the asset\n- A payment iQube describing the QriptoCENT transfer\n\nBy returning only references or signed claims to the thin client, you preserve security while still giving the client what it needs to render the experience.\n\n## 4. Tenant and estate controls\n\nIn a multi tenant environment, admin Aigents can:\n\n- Set Q¢ price bands and policies per tenant\n- Control which capabilities are exposed via A2A endpoints\n- Monitor aggregate flows of QriptoCENT\n\nYour A2A API should always respect these controls by querying governance iQubes or policy Aigents before executing value flows.\n\n## 5. Observability\n\nFinally, wire in logs and metrics so you can monitor:\n\n- Call volumes by endpoint and tenant\n- QriptoCENT consumed and earned\n- Error rates and latency\n\nThis data becomes vital input for Exec level dashboards and optimisation work.\n",
              "duration": "7 min read"
            }
          },
