          "contentId": "1c89d604-106f-4ed4-8477-eafe3fd3a3a4",
          "title": "Securing QriptoCENT Flows with iQubes, DIDs and Keys",
          "type": "tutorial",
          "format": "article",
          "content": {},
          "excerpt": "Design patterns for keeping QriptoCENT movements safe using iQube primitives and DID-based identity.",
          "placement": {
            "tab": "dev",
            "imageX": 50,
            "imageY": 50,
            "section": "21knowdz",
            "position": 4,
            "imageScale": 105,
            "imagePosition": "center"
          },
          "modalities": {
            "link": {
              "url": "https://qripto.net/docs/security/iqube-and-qcent",
              "allow_embed": false
            },
            "read": {
              "text": "# Securing QriptoCENT flows with iQubes, DIDs and keys\n\nAs soon as you move real value, security stops being optional. In the Qripto stack, security is not only about keys and signatures; it is also about how you design and partition iQubes.\n\nThis guide outlines practical patterns for keeping QriptoCENT flows safe.\n\n## Think object security before perimeter security\n\nTraditional systems focus on defending a perimeter. In an iQube world, you secure the objects themselves:\n\n- Sensitive payloads live in blakQubes, encrypted at rest\n- Public facing metadata sits in metaQubes\n- Rights and value flows are expressed via tokenQubes that can be priced and settled in QriptoCENT\n\nEven if one layer is compromised, the others can still enforce constraints.\n\n## DIDs and persona layers\n\nIdentity is represented with DIDs and personas:\n\n- A deep, rarely exposed KybeDID anchors long term personhood\n- Root DIDs and proxies handle high-assurance or regulated interactions\n- Everyday activity happens via persona level identifiers\n\nFor QriptoCENT flows you should:\n\n- Use persona level keys for routine transactions\n- Only involve Root DID proxies when required by policy or regulation\n- Ensure that Aigents never require direct access to KybeDID level material\n\n## Key handling patterns\n\nAs a developer you should:\n\n- Keep signing keys in hardware where possible or in hardened custody services\n- Ensure separation between keys used for QriptoCENT movement and those used for other actions\n- Rotate keys on a schedule and when risk signals appear\n\nWhere Aigents sign on behalf of users, make the delegation explicit in iQubes and easy to revoke.\n\n## iQube level controls for Q¢\n\nEach tokenQube that represents a QriptoCENT obligation can carry:\n\n- Limits on frequency and amount per time window\n- Allowed counterparties or Aigent classes\n- Clawback or dispute procedures\n\nBy reading these constraints before executing a Q¢ transfer, Aigents can enforce user and tenant policy automatically.\n\n## Logging, audits and risk cohorts\n\nEvery QriptoCENT movement should yield:\n\n- A durable log entry containing hashed references to the iQubes involved\n- Signals for cohort level risk logic, so suspicious behaviour is pushed to the edges\n\nAudit Aigents can then reconstruct flows without needing to see private payloads, preserving sovereignty while still enabling accountability.\n",
              "duration": "8 min read"
            }
          },
